          <span class="s1">&lt;div </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;body&quot; </span><span class="s2">role</span><span class="s3">=&quot;main&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
            
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;putting-it-all-together&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;makegames-6&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;id1&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;h2&gt;</span><span class="s0">6. Putting it all together</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#makegames-6&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">So far you've learnt all the basics necessary to build a simple game. You should understand how to create Pygame objects, how Pygame</span>
<span class="s0">displays objects, how it handles events, and how you can use physics to introduce some motion into your game. Now I'll just show how</span>
<span class="s0">you can take all those chunks of code and put them together into a working game. What we need first is to let the ball hit the sides</span>
<span class="s0">of the screen, and for the bat to be able to hit the ball, otherwise there's not going to be much game play involved. We do this</span>
<span class="s0">using Pygame's </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/rect.html#pygame.Rect.collidepoint&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pygame.Rect.collidepoint&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">collision</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; </span><span class="s0">methods.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;let-the-ball-hit-sides&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;makegames-6-1&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">6.1. Let the ball hit sides</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#let-the-ball-hit-sides&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The basics principle behind making it bounce of the sides is easy to grasp. You grab the coordinates of the four corners of the ball,</span>
<span class="s0">and check to see if they correspond with the x or y coordinate of the edge of the screen. So if the top right and top left corners both</span>
<span class="s0">have a y coordinate of zero, you know that the ball is currently on the top edge of the screen. <span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Here we check to see if the </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">area</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span>
<span class="s0">contains the new position of the ball (it always should, so we needn't have an </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">else</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">clause,</span>
<span class="s0">though in other circumstances you might want to consider it. We then check if the coordinates for the four corners</span>
<span class="s0">are </span><span class="s1">&lt;em&gt;</span><span class="s0">colliding</span><span class="s1">&lt;/em&gt; </span><span class="s0">with the area's edges, and create objects for each result. If they are, the objects will have a value of 1,</span>
<span class="s0">or </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">True</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">. If they don't, then the value will be </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">None</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">, or </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">False</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">. We then see if it has hit the top or bottom, and if it</span>
<span class="s0">has we change the ball's direction. Handily, using radians we can do this by simply reversing its positive/negative value.</span>
<span class="s0">We also check to see if the ball has gone off the sides, and if it has we call the </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">offcourt</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">function.</span>
<span class="s0">This, in my game, resets the ball, adds 1 point to the score of the player specified when calling the function, and displays the new score.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Finally, we recompile the vector based on the new angle. And that is it. The ball will now merrily bounce off the walls and go</span>
<span class="s0">offcourt with good grace.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

    <span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;k&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">elif</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">:</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
        <span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">=</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;ow&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">not</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;bp&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">vector</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;o&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">=</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">(</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">angle</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">,</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;n&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">z</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;p&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">)</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">We start this section with an </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">else</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">statement, because this carries on from the previous chunk of code to check if the ball</span>
<span class="s0">hits the sides. It makes sense that if it doesn't hit the sides, it might hit a bat, so we carry on the conditional statement. The</span>
<span class="s0">first glitch to fix is to shrink the players' rectangles by 3 pixels in both dimensions, to stop the bat catching a ball that goes</span>
<span class="s0">behind them (if you imagine you just move the bat so that as the ball travels behind it, the rectangles overlap, and so normally the</span>
<span class="s0">ball would then have been </span><span class="s4">&amp;quot;</span><span class="s0">hit</span><span class="s4">&amp;quot; </span><span class="s0">- this prevents that).</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">Next we check if the rectangles collide, with one more glitch fix. Notice that I've commented on these odd bits of code - it's always</span>
<span class="s0">good to explain bits of code that are abnormal, both for others who look at your code, and so you understand it when you come back to</span>
<span class="s0">it. The without the fix, the ball might hit a corner of the bat, change direction, and one frame later still find itself inside the</span>
<span class="s0">bat. Then it would again think it has been hit, and change its direction. This can happen several times, making the ball's motion</span>
<span class="s0">completely unrealistic. So we have a variable, </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self.hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">, which we set to </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">True</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">when it has been hit, and </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">False</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">one frame</span>
<span class="s0">later. When we check if the rectangles have collided, we also check if </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self.hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">is </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">True</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">/</span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">False</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;</span><span class="s0">, to stop internal bouncing.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The important code here is pretty easy to understand. All rectangles have a </span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;reference internal&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;../ref/rect.html#pygame.Rect.colliderect&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pygame.Rect.colliderect&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;xref py py-meth docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">colliderect</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</span>
<span class="s0">function, into which you feed the rectangle of another object, which returns </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">True</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">if the rectangles do overlap, and </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">False</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">if not.</span>
<span class="s0">If they do, we can change the direction by subtracting the current angle from </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">pi</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">(again, a handy trick you can do with radians,</span>
<span class="s0">which will adjust the angle by 90 degrees and send it off in the right direction; you might find at this point that a thorough</span>
<span class="s0">understanding of radians is in order!). Just to finish the glitch checking, we switch </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">self.hit</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">back to </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">False</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">if it's the frame</span>
<span class="s0">after they were hit.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">We also then recompile the vector. You would of course want to remove the same line in the previous chunk of code, so that you only do</span>
<span class="s0">this once after the </span><span class="s1">&lt;code </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;docutils literal notranslate&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;span </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;pre&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0">if-else</span><span class="s1">&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt; </span><span class="s0">conditional statement. And that's it! The combined code will now allow the ball to hit sides and bats.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;section </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;the-finished-product&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;span </span><span class="s2">id</span><span class="s3">=&quot;makegames-6-3&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;h3&gt;</span><span class="s0">6.3. The Finished product</span><span class="s1">&lt;a </span><span class="s2">class</span><span class="s3">=&quot;headerlink&quot; </span><span class="s2">href</span><span class="s3">=&quot;#the-finished-product&quot; </span><span class="s2">title</span><span class="s3">=&quot;Permalink to this heading&quot;</span><span class="s1">&gt;</span><span class="s0"></span><span class="s1">&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">The final product, with all the bits of code thrown together, as well as some other bits ofcode to glue it all together, will look</span>
<span class="s0">like this:</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>

<span class="s1">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class="s0">As well as showing you the final product, I'll point you back to TomPong, upon which all of this is based. Download it, have a look</span>
<span class="s0">at the source code, and you'll see a full implementation of pong using all of the code you've seen in this tutorial, as well as lots of</span>
<span class="s0">other code I've added in various versions, such as some extra physics for spinning, and various other bug and glitch fixes.</span><span class="s1">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
